    <h1>Three Modes</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 1 · Peirce 1878, 1903</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">This book treats reasoning as reducible to three operations: deduction, induction, and abduction. The first two have millennia of formalization behind them. The third was named in 1878 and lacks a general quantitative measure comparable to deductive validity or statistical inference. This chapter defines all three, shows that complex reasoning decomposes into compositions of them, and reaches the limit: we can name abduction but cannot yet measure it.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The dog that didn't bark</h2>

    <blockquote>
      <p>"Is there any other point to which you would wish to draw my attention?"</p>
      <p>"To the curious incident of the dog in the night-time."</p>
      <p>"The dog did nothing in the night-time."</p>
      <p>"That was the curious incident."</p>
      <p style="text-align:right; font-style:normal;">— Arthur Conan Doyle, <em>The Adventure of Silver Blaze</em> (1892)</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>Holmesian reasoning is usually described as deduction. This case is not deduction. You can reconstruct a deductive argument after the fact: dogs bark at strangers; this dog did not bark; therefore the intruder was not a stranger. But where did the first premise come from? Holmes knows a thousand things about dogs, stables, night, and strangers. The work is not in the syllogism. The work is in selecting which fact to attend to: the silence of the dog rather than the condition of the lock, the weather, the groom's alibi, the colour of the horse. The absence is the signal. The quiet night is the background. Separating signal from background is the operation Doyle misnamed.</p>

    <p>That operation is the neglected third mode of reasoning. Sharp diagnosticians do it fast: separate what matters from what doesn't. Every working scientist, doctor, engineer, and detective performs it constantly. They often have local names for it — diagnosis, root cause analysis, hypothesis generation — but no shared theory.</p>

    <h2>Three modes, three Latin roots</h2>

    <p>Charles Sanders Peirce identified the trichotomy in 1878 and refined it over the next twenty-five years. All three terms derive from Latin <em>ducere</em> ("to lead"):</p>

    <p><strong>Deduction</strong> (<em>de-ducere</em>, "to lead from"): given premises, derive consequences. If all men are mortal and Socrates is a man, then Socrates is mortal. The conclusion adds nothing that wasn't already contained in the premises. Deduction has two millennia of formalisation behind it, from Aristotle's syllogisms through Frege's predicate logic to modern theorem provers, type checkers, and SAT solvers.</p>

    <p><strong>Induction</strong> (<em>in-ducere</em>, "to lead toward"): given examples, generalise a pattern. Every swan I've seen is white; probably all swans are white. The conclusion extends beyond the observed cases but stays within the same conceptual frame. Induction was elevated to systematic method by Francis Bacon in 1620, formalised by Fisher and Neyman in the twentieth century, and underpins much of statistics and machine learning.</p>

    <p><strong>Abduction</strong> (<em>ab-ducere</em>, "to lead away"): given a surprising observation, propose what would make it unsurprising. The lawn is wet but it didn't rain; perhaps the sprinkler ran overnight. The conclusion goes beyond both the premises and the observed data. It introduces a new idea. Peirce gave this mode its classic treatment in 1878 under the name <em>hypothesis</em>, later also calling it <em>abduction</em> or <em>retroduction</em>. It lacks a general quantitative framework comparable to deductive validity or statistical inference.</p>

    <h2>The formal syllogisms</h2>

    <p>Peirce often illustrated the three modes with a single example rotated three ways. The classic version uses beans:</p>

