      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Mode</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Premises</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Conclusion</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Status</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Deduction</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">All beans from this bag are white. These beans are from this bag.</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">These beans are white.</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Certain</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Induction</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">These beans are from this bag. These beans are white.</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">All beans from this bag are white.</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Probable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Abduction</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">All beans from this bag are white. These beans are white.</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">These beans are from this bag.</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Plausible</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Each mode rearranges the same three propositions (Rule, Case, Result). Deduction goes from Rule + Case to Result. Induction goes from Case + Result to Rule. Abduction goes from Rule + Result to Case. The logical form is symmetric; the epistemic status is not. Deduction preserves truth with certainty. Induction converges on truth under assumptions (sufficient samples, stable distribution). Abduction proposes a candidate explanation that might be entirely wrong.</p>

    <h2>Why three and only three</h2>

    <p>In his 1903 Harvard lectures, Peirce argued that the trichotomy is exhaustive. The argument rests on his theory of categories: there are exactly three irreducible kinds of relation.</p>

    <p>A <strong>monadic</strong> relation is a quality of a single thing. A <strong>dyadic</strong> relation connects two things (cause and effect, stimulus and response). A <strong>triadic</strong> relation connects three things in a way that cannot be reduced to pairs (a sign, the object it represents, and the interpretation it produces).</p>

    <p>One way to motivate the trichotomy is through Peirce's categories. Deduction is monadic: it unpacks what is already implicit in the premises. Induction is dyadic: it correlates cases with results. Abduction is triadic: it relates an observation, a rule, and a case in a way that neither deduction nor induction can capture. Since monadic, dyadic, and triadic relations exhaust the irreducible types, three modes exhaust the kinds of inference.</p>

    <p>Whether this argument succeeds is debatable. The working bet of this book is that apparent fourth modes reduce to compositions of the three. No counterexample has survived scrutiny so far, but the claim is empirical, not proven.</p>

    <h2>The triangle</h2>

    <p>The three modes form a cycle. Each mode takes one kind of thing and produces another:</p>

    <p><strong>Abduction</strong>: Observation → Theory. You observe something surprising — a symptom, a bug, an anomaly. You propose an explanation: a hypothesis about what is true. This is the creative step, the one that introduces new ideas into inquiry.</p>

    <p><strong>Deduction</strong>: Theory → Experiment. Given the hypothesis, you derive its consequences: if this theory is true, then we should observe X under conditions Y. This is the planning step, turning knowledge into procedure.</p>

    <p><strong>Induction</strong>: Experiment → Observation. You run the experiment, accumulate evidence, and compare the results to the prediction. The new observations feed back into the cycle. This is the testing step.</p>

    <div style="max-width:min(460px, 100%); margin:1.5em auto;">
      <img src="/assets/modes-of-reason-triangle.svg" alt="Triangle: Observation → Theory (abduction), Theory → Experiment (deduction), Experiment → Observation (induction). Three modes, three edges, one cycle." style="width:100%; display:block;">
    </div>

    <p>The triangle is a decomposition, not decoration. A self-correcting empirical inquiry eventually traverses all three edges. Partial traversals are partial inquiries: a hypothesis without a test (abduction alone), a test without a hypothesis (induction alone), a prediction without data (deduction alone). The cycle is what makes inquiry self-correcting.</p>

    <h2>Examples across domains</h2>

    <p>The triangle appears in medicine, engineering, science, and daily life. The vocabulary changes; the structure does not.</p>

    <p><strong>Medicine.</strong> A patient presents with fever, joint pain, and a butterfly-shaped facial rash. The doctor proposes lupus (abduction: observation → theory). If lupus, then antinuclear antibodies should be elevated (deduction: theory → experiment). The lab runs the ANA test and reports a high titer (induction: experiment → observation). A positive ANA supports but does not confirm lupus — ANA is sensitive, not specific. The new observation narrows the differential or forces a new hypothesis.</p>

    <p><strong>Debugging.</strong> A server returns 500 errors on every third request. The engineer proposes a connection pool exhaustion bug (abduction). If the pool is exhausted, then active connections should climb to the pool limit before failures begin (deduction). The engineer checks the connection count at failure time (induction). The errors persist — so the hypothesis was wrong. The engineer abduces again: maybe it's a thread-safety issue in the request handler.</p>

    <p><strong>Science.</strong> Darwin observed that finch beak shapes vary across Galapagos islands (observation). He proposed that beak shape tracks food source — different environments select for different beaks (abduction). If natural selection drives beak shape, then islands with hard seeds should have finches with stronger beaks (deduction). Decades of field measurement confirmed the correlation (induction).</p>

    <p><strong>Everyday life.</strong> You flip a light switch and nothing happens (observation). You hypothesise that the bulb burned out (abduction). If the bulb is dead, then replacing it should fix the problem (deduction). You replace the bulb and the light turns on (induction).</p>

    <h2>Everything decomposes</h2>

    <p>Three primitives. Complex reasoning decomposes into compositions of them:</p>

    <p><strong>Analogy</strong> = abduction (notice a surprising similarity across two domains) + induction (generalise the structural correspondence). Peirce analysed it this way. <a href="https://cyber.harvard.edu/bridge/Library/brewer.htm">Brewer's</a> account of legal reasoning supports the same decomposition.</p>

    <p><strong>Diagnosis</strong> = abduction (propose what is wrong) + deduction (derive the observable consequences of that fault).</p>

    <p><strong>Scientific method</strong> = abduction (hypothesise) + deduction (predict) + induction (test). The full triangle.</p>

    <p><strong>Debugging</strong> = abduction (propose a cause) + deduction (if this cause, then that symptom) + abduction again (it wasn't that; next cause). Debugging is typically abduction-heavy because the hypothesis space is large and each test eliminates only one candidate.</p>

    <p><strong>Legal precedent</strong> = abduction (match the current case to a prior case) + induction (generalise a principle from the precedent) + deduction (apply the generalised rule to the current facts).</p>

    <p>Holmes, House, Semmelweis, Darwin. All running the same compositions. Doyle misnamed the mode; his characters perform it regardless.</p>

    <h2>Prior art</h2>

    <p>The trichotomy did not appear from nowhere. It accumulated over twenty-three centuries.</p>

