    <h2>Cross-field recurrence</h2>

    <p>Abduction keeps getting rediscovered. At least eight entries across six fields describe the same pattern: given an observation, separate what demands attention from what can be held constant. Gestalt psychologists call it figure-ground segregation. Piaget called it equilibration. Calcagno calls it bi-abduction. Each field coined its own term. Chapter 3 lays out the full table and extracts the common structure.</p>

    <h2>What breaks</h2>

    <p>We have enough of a taxonomy to state the next problem. Three modes, defined. A cycle connecting them. Evidence of cross-field recurrence. Decomposition rules that reduce complex reasoning to compositions of the three primitives.</p>

    <p>But we cannot <em>measure</em> abduction. We can say that it is "more fertile" than deduction and "less certain" than induction, but those are ordinal claims, not quantitative ones. How fertile? How uncertain? Is there a formal tradeoff between fertility and certainty, or is the relationship vague? Can we compare two abductive inferences and say which is better, before testing either one?</p>

    <p>Peirce addressed this late in life with two terms: <strong>security</strong> (how certain is the conclusion?) and <strong>uberty</strong> (how much new knowledge does it produce?). He claimed that security and uberty are inversely related — that the tradeoff is structural, not accidental. If he's right, the tradeoff constrains the design space of any system that reasons. If he's wrong, abduction is just guessing with extra syllables.</p>

    <p>That tradeoff is the subject of <a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch02-security-uberty/">Chapter 2</a>.</p>

